`,n.jsx(e.h2,{children:"Introduction"}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:"ISRO research internships expose students to national space missions, embedded systems, remote sensing payloads, and data processing pipelines. This guide consolidates how centres like VSSC, URSC, SAC, NRSC, ISTRAC, LPSC, IPRC, and SDSC handle applications, what timelines to expect for summer 2026, and how to prepare a portfolio that survives technical screening. Any dates marked Expected/Indicative mirror prior-year cycles; confirm with the hosting centres latest circular."}),`
`,n.jsx(e.h2,{children:"About the Organization / Institute"}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:"The Indian Space Research Organisation leads Indias launch vehicles, spacecraft, earth observation, and deep-space missions. Each centre runs specific mandatesVSSC (launch vehicles), URSC (satellites), SAC/NRSC (payloads and data), ISTRAC (tracking), LPSC/IPRC (propulsion), SDSC (launch ops). Interns typically join engineering or science divisions aligned to ongoing missions or technology development."}),`
`,n.jsx(e.h2,{children:"Overview of the Research Internship Programme"}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:"ISRO offers short-term project training and internships for students nominated by their universities or selected through centre-level calls. Engagements are on-site, supervised by a scientist/engineer, and culminate in a project report or demo. Slots are limited and tied to mentor availability; some centres require an official request letter from the universitys Head of Department."}),`
